The number of filled cells among A, B, C, D, F, G, H, I is 2 or 3 (since E has 8 neighbors, which are A, B, C, D, F, G, H, I). So, sum(A, B, C, D, F, G, H, I) {2, 3} 2. For each cell in the subgrid (excluding E), the number of filled neighbors is not 2 or 3. Lets break down the constraints for each cell: - **Cell A (1,1)** has neighbors: B, D, E. So, neighbors_in_subgrid = {B, D, E} - **Cell B (1,2)** has neighbors: A, C, D, E, F. Neighbors_in_subgrid = {A, C, D, E, F} - **Cell C (1,3)** has neighbors: B, F, E. Neighbors_in_subgrid = {B, F, E} - **Cell D (2,1)** has neighbors: A, B, G, E, H. Neighbors_in_subgrid = {A, B, G, E, H} - **Cell F (2,3)** has neighbors: B, C, D, H, E. Neighbors_in_subgrid = {B, C, D, H, E} - **Cell G (3,1)** has neighbors: D, H, E. Neighbors_in_subgrid = {D, H, E} - **Cell H (3,2)** has neighbors: D, F, G, E, I. Neighbors_in_subgrid = {D, F, G, E, I} - **Cell I (3,3)** has neighbors: H, E. Neighbors_in_subgrid = {H, E} Therefore, for each cell, the number of filled neighbors is the sum of the variables corresponding to their neighbors_in_subgrid.
